
## ðŸ§  What is DOM Manipulation?

DOM (Document Object Model) represents the structure of your HTML page as a tree of objects. JavaScript lets you **interact with and modify** this structure dynamically.

---

## ðŸ”¹ 1. Selecting Elements

### âœ… `document.querySelector()` and `document.querySelectorAll()`

```html
<p id="greeting">Hello!</p>
```

```javascript
const para = document.querySelector("#greeting"); // selects first element with id="greeting"
console.log(para.textContent); // "Hello!"
```

```html
<ul>
  <li class="item">One</li>
  <li class="item">Two</li>
</ul>
```

```javascript
const items = document.querySelectorAll(".item"); // selects all elements with class="item"
items.forEach(item => console.log(item.textContent));
```

---

## ðŸ”¹ 2. Modifying Content

### âœ… `.textContent`, `.innerHTML`, `.value`

```javascript
para.textContent = "Welcome, Santosh!"; // changes text
para.innerHTML = "<strong>Welcome!</strong>"; // inserts HTML
```

For input fields:
```html
<input type="text" id="nameInput" />
```

```javascript
document.querySelector("#nameInput").value = "Santosh";
```

---

## ðŸ”¹ 3. Styling Elements

### âœ… `.style` and `.classList`

```javascript
para.style.color = "blue";
para.style.fontSize = "20px";
```

Using classes:
```css
.highlight {
  background-color: yellow;
  font-weight: bold;
}
```

```javascript
para.classList.add("highlight"); // adds class
para.classList.remove("highlight"); // removes class
para.classList.toggle("highlight"); // toggles class
```

---

## ðŸ”¹ 4. Handling Events

### âœ… `addEventListener()`

```html
<button id="clickMe">Click Me</button>
```

```javascript
const btn = document.querySelector("#clickMe");

btn.addEventListener("click", function() {
  alert("Button clicked!");
});
```

You can also use arrow functions:
```javascript
btn.addEventListener("mouseover", () => {
  btn.style.backgroundColor = "lightgreen";
});
```

---

## ðŸ§ª Mini Demo: Putting It All Together

```html
<input type="text" id="name" placeholder="Enter your name" />
<button id="submitBtn">Greet</button>
<p id="output"></p>
```

```javascript
document.querySelector("#submitBtn").addEventListener("click", () => {
  const name = document.querySelector("#name").value;
  const output = document.querySelector("#output");
  output.textContent = `Hello, ${name}!`;
  output.classList.add("highlight");
});
```

